name: 5-pyrimidinecarboxylic acid, 1,2,3,4-tetrahydro-6-methyl-2-oxo-4-[2-(trifluoromethyl)phenyl]-, ethyl ester
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-4066
Reason:
To predict the melting point for this compound, we consider the effects of various functional groups and structural features on the basic pyrimidine structure. The basic pyrimidine ring has a melting point around 20-22°C. Each functional group or structural feature has a characteristic influence on the melting point:
- Methyl group: +15°C (increases hydrophobicity and molecular weight)
- Ethyl ester group: +20°C (due to additional hydrophobicity and molecular weight, as well as providing some rigidity to the molecule)
- 1,2,3,4-tetrahydro modification: +50°C (saturating the ring increases the melting point due to increased van der Waals interactions and reduces molecular planarity)
- Trifluoromethyl group: +40°C (highly electronegative, increases intermolecular interactions due to dipole induction)
- Carboxylic acid: +30°C (forms strong hydrogen bonds which significantly increase the melting point)
- Additional aromatic ring: +30°C (provides additional rigidity and pi-pi interactions)
- Ketone: +10°C (polar carbonyl group can form additional intermolecular forces)

Adding all these increments to the base value of the pyrimidine ring, we get an estimated melting point for the compound.
